Old Ruthenian is definitely a more neutral term, and you can't just keep subtle propaganda regarding the pattern of listing and expect it to be fact. The original listing was definitely not alphabetically or by number of speakers - far more people speak Ukrainian than Belarusian. Also, yes, Ukrainian is closest to Old East Slavic, as confirmed in many articles and analyses. Denial of these hard facts points to your dishonest propagandist agenda, something perpetuated by obvious Russian agents.

Old Ruthenian is a more neutral term. A better question would be why is Ukrainian mentioned last when it is both closest to Old East Slavic, and the previous listing follows no distinct pattern? The previous one was far more ideologically motivated, considering the Ukrainophobic propaganda churned out on articles pertaining to Ukraine across this site.
